BSE, BOVINE - UK (03): (SCOTLAND) CLASSICAL C-TYPE, INVESTIGATION, CONTROL
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 31 Oct 2018
Source: BBC News [edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-46045955


So-called "mad cow disease" was discovered after a 5-year-old animal died at Boghead Farm in Lumsden. The carcasses, described as 3 cohorts and one offspring, are now being tested at a specialist facility in Dumfries. The Scottish government insists there is "no risk to consumer health."

The news of the culling was confirmed during a session of the rural economy committee at Holyrood, when Conservative MSP Peter Chapman asked Mr Ewing how the BSE investigations were going.

The cabinet secretary replied, "The news is hugely disappointing to have the confirmed case of BSE in Aberdeenshire. There is no risk to consumer health. The Scottish government has activated plans to protect food safety and the valuable farming industry."

The investigation would take time, he said, and he asked senior official Elinor Mitchell to explain.

Mitchell said, "Yesterday, the 3 cohort animals and one offspring were culled on the farm. The carcasses have been transported for sampling and disposal to Dumfries. Tests will determine if the carcasses are then taken to the APHA Weybridge offices for further testing."

The isolated case involves Boghead Farm in Lumsden. There have been 16 cases of BSE in the UK in the past 7 years.

In contrast, thousands of cattle were infected at the height of the BSE crisis back in the 1980s and 1990s. More than 4 million animals were slaughtered in an attempt to halt the disease.

