Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The described classic BARB (born after the ban) BSE in a 5-year-old cow in Scotland warrants, according to EU requirements, a thorough investigation, on top of the prescribed detection, culling, and testing of its cohorts and progeny (which can be found on one or more farms). A particular attention is paid to the 1st months of the cow's life, when the infection takes place, and to the composition and origin of feed and milk replacers used on the index farm preceding and during the birth year of the affected animal. Investigations of BARB cases can be particularly difficult due to the time lag between exposure to the BSE agent and the onset of clinical signs, the small number of cases (making attribution of source difficult), loss of paper records, and changes in farm management.

A scientific opinion from the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) recommended the creation of a predefined set of epidemiological data to be collected across the EU for the investigation of suspected and confirmed BSE cases.

Irish investigators have recently published the detailed course and methods applied during their investigation of a classic BARB BSE case in 2015 involving a dairy cow that remained, throughout her life, on the premises where she was born in 2010 and eventually euthanised after a short disease/recumbency. They presented an epidemiological framework and a questionnaire to aid the investigation of suspect and confirmed BSE cases. The framework focuses on confirmation and discrimination, estimating the date and location of exposure, and determining the method/source of exposure. The questionnaire (with 135 questions) aids data collection.

The authors recommended that the framework and questionnaire are used concurrently.

References
1. O' Connor JT, Byrne JP, More SJ, Blake M et al. Using an epidemiological framework and bovine spongiform encephalopathy investigation questionnaire to investigate suspect bovine spongiform encephalopathy cases: an example from a bovine spongiform encephalopathy case in Ireland in 2015. Veterinary Record. 2018; 182 (6): 168. https://veterinaryrecord.bmj.com/content/182/6/168

- Mod.AS

